34
00:02:04.610 --> 00:02:08.450
They eventually decided, do these
interviews actually make any difference?

35
00:02:08.450 --> 00:02:11.670
They had read the literature which
raises the question about how diagnostic

36
00:02:11.670 --> 00:02:14.790
interviews really are and ran the numbers.

37
00:02:14.790 --> 00:02:19.030
What they found was they were not
very good at predicting interviews,

38
00:02:19.030 --> 00:02:22.520
were not very good at predicting
employee performance down the road.

39
00:02:22.520 --> 00:02:24.960
This is a real problem
whenever you're spending

40
00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:29.870
ten managers interview time on every
potential hire that comes through.

41
00:02:29.870 --> 00:02:32.980
As a result, they did something
that is very un Google like.

42
00:02:32.980 --> 00:02:38.430
They provided an edict from above
which they never do that said,

43
00:02:38.430 --> 00:02:40.990
you can't schedule more than four

44
00:02:40.990 --> 00:02:44.470
interviews with managers when you
have a potential hire come through.

45
00:02:44.470 --> 00:02:48.920
You just can't spend that amount of our
resources because we've run the numbers

46
00:02:48.920 --> 00:02:50.350
and it's not worth it.

47
00:02:50.350 --> 00:02:53.280
It's not worth,
the analytics say it's not worth it.

