00:03:03.540 --> 00:03:05.630
And an example from Credit Suisse.

52
00:03:05.630 --> 00:03:09.310
Credit Suisse believes that a 1% increase
in their retention, if they can retain

53
00:03:09.310 --> 00:03:12.910
their employees, they can save the company
75 to $100 million dollars a year.

54
00:03:12.910 --> 00:03:16.690
So financial services, one of the most
important assets is the people.

55
00:03:16.690 --> 00:03:18.630
They're going to try to retain their
best people a little bit longer and

56
00:03:18.630 --> 00:03:20.030
a little more effectively.

57
00:03:20.030 --> 00:03:23.780
They did this with a three year study,
looking at factors that

58
00:03:23.780 --> 00:03:27.050
led the people to leave the firm, or
led people to stay within the firm.

59
00:03:27.050 --> 00:03:31.960
One of the things they found,
one of the surprising results was that

60
00:03:31.960 --> 00:03:36.580
those who changed jobs internally were
more likely to stay with the firm.

61
00:03:36.580 --> 00:03:37.610
They call this stickiness.

62
00:03:37.610 --> 00:03:41.630
They said changing jobs increases
an employee's stickiness.

63
00:03:41.630 --> 00:03:43.230
Once they identified that,

64
00:03:43.230 --> 00:03:47.660
they had some levers they could
pull to push for more stickiness.

65
00:03:47.660 --> 00:03:53.130
So for example, prior to that
analysis they had posted internally,

66
00:03:53.130 --> 00:03:56.080
less than 50% of the new
jobs that came up.

67
00:03:56.080 --> 00:03:59.950
But because of that analysis, they
realized we need to be placing our people,

68
00:03:59.950 --> 00:04:03.390
moving our people more rather
than letting them leave the firm.

69
00:04:03.390 --> 00:04:08.062
So they increased the postings to more
than 80% now of the new openings get

70
00:04:08.062 --> 00:04:12.077
posted internally, leading to
hundreds more internal hires and

71
00:04:12.077 --> 00:04:16.457
according to the models more sticky
employees, lower retention, and

72
00:04:16.457 --> 00:04:19.180
ultimately, higher earnings.

73
